    en: "An interested party can object to the probate of a will in New York — a distributee (intestate heir), a beneficiary under a prior will, or another person adversely affected. SCPA Section 1404 gives the potential objectant a pre-objection examination of the attesting witnesses, the drafting attorney, the nominated executors, and the person who supervised execution. The examination is meant to let the objectant decide whether formal objections are warranted. Grounds for objection: lack of due execution, lack of testamentary capacity, undue influence, fraud, forgery, or revocation. The estate pays the cost of examinations before objections are filed; the objectant pays if the examination happens after objections are filed."
